{{italictitle}}
The '''''Annales ianuenses''''' ([[Latin]]: "Genoese annals") or '''''Annali Genovesi''''' form the [[official history]] of the [[Republic of Genoa]] during the [[High Middle Ages]].{{sfn|McCormick|1991}} It is the earliest medieval civic chronicle and the earliest set of annals composed by a layman.{{sfn|Bellomo|2013}} The ''Annales'' form a chronological account of the [[Timeline of Genoese history|history of Genoa]] from 1099 until 1294. The first annals were composed by [[Caffarus]], a private citizen, on his own initiative. In 1152, he petitioned the republic to keep a copy in the public archives (''comuni cartularium'') and thenceforth the annals were continued at public expense.{{sfn|Wickham|1992|p=173}} Caffarus, who probably began the work around 1100, continued it himself down to 1163. A series of officials of the chancery continued the ''Annales'' between 1169 and 1197, when work was taken over by the scribe and diplomat Ogerius.{{sfn|McCormick|1991}} He worked down to 1216; thereafter, the annalists were anonymous, and at times a committee, until the last entry was added in 1294.{{sfn|McCormick|1991}} The public manuscript of the ''Annales ianuenses'' is now kept in the [[Bibliothèque nationale de France]], lat. 10136.{{sfn|McCormick|1991}}

The content of the annals is confined to the names of the consuls, the changes to the constitution (the ''compagniae'' or sworn association), changes to the coinage and the victories of Genoa over her enemies, particularly [[Saracens]] and [[Republic of Pisa|Pisans]].{{sfn|Wickham|1992|p=173}} In Caffarus' own words to the republic in 1152, the purpose of the chronicle was "that henceforth for all time the victories of the city of Genoa be known to future men."{{sfn|Wickham|1992|p=173}}

