{{Infobox museum |name=''Geelong Maritime Museum |image= |caption= |established=1989 |location='The Stables', [[Osborne House (Geelong)|Osborne House]], Swinburn Street, North Geelong Victoria, Australia |type=[[Maritime museum]] |visitors= |coordinates = {{coord|-38.118708|144.358164|display=inline}} |director= |website= }}
The '''Geelong Maritime Museum''' is a volunteer-run Community group or not-for-profit historical museum located at 'The Stables', Osborne House, Swinburn Street, North Geelong Victoria, Australia since 1993.<ref>[http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/ahdb/search.pl?mode=place_detail;place_id=3651 Australian Heritage Database Osborne House, Place ID 3651]</ref> The Museum was founded in about 1989, with ex Royal Navy Ldg. Tel, Robert Henry (Bob) Appleton OAM as the foundation Honorary Curator.<ref>[http://www.upperiscope.net.au/uploads/1/9/6/6/19663981/bob_appleton.doc ''Up Periscope'' Submarine Association of Australia]</ref> The Museum collects and displays historic artefacts and documents related to the Maritime History of geelong and Victoria, and the history of the Victorian and Australian Navy's.
The Geelong Maritime Museum is housed in the renovated stables of [[Osborne House (Geelong)|Osborne House]], which was built in 1858 for local squatter, Robert Muirhead. Following a number of private owners, the building was the purchased by the Victorian State Government in 1900 as country residence for the Governor of Victoria, but never used for this purpose. Instead, it was bought by the Geelong Harbour Trust in 1905, and subsequently became the first Australian Naval College from 1913 to 1915,<ref>''Royal Australian Naval College - Inspection and report on sites and suggested sites'', NAA: MP472/1 18/13/5650, National Archives of Australia</ref><ref>''Site for Naval College, Jervis Bay'', NAA: A6273 L1925/952, National Archives of Australia</ref> a military hospital during the World War One, and the first home for the J Class Submarine of the Royal Australian Navy’s submarine service between 1919 and 1924. The Geelong Harbour Trust resumed control in 1929, and the Shire of Corio moved in <!-- not a mistake-->in 1938. It was a training centre for the army during World War Two, followed by the Corio Shire Council from 1943 to 1995 when the shire merged with the City of Geelong.<ref>[http://www.intown.com.au/locals/geelong/attractions/geelong-naval-and-maritime-museum.htm Intown Geelong 2014]</ref>
Displays at the museum include scale models of ships that either visited Geelong or called the port home and relics of the trade and navigation, as well as uniforms, weaponry and other naval artefacts. Exhibitions also presents the [[HMVS Cerberus]] Gun Turret and the helm of the [[HMVS Nelson]].<ref>[http://mhhv.org.au/?p=2315 Military History & Heritage Victoria 2012 Military History & Heritage Victoria]</ref>
